<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>LOCAL GOVERNMENT PROCUREMENT: SECURING ECONOMIC GROWTH AND BETTER VALUE</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">LGO 81</span></p><h2 style="line-height:14.5pt; margin:17pt 0pt 10pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Submission from Colin Cram </span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">government procurement spend of £45bn a year represents a huge opportunity for investment in the UK and local economies, whilst delivering improved value for money for taxpayers. Local government has not, overall, delivered these objectives because of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> fragmented management of its procurement spend, lack of coherent strategy and limited expertise available to most councils. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A policy of local procurement, without a much more sophisticated approach, is a zero sum game. Some councils will benefit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Other</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will lose. A coherent and more sophisticated approach is needed to boost overall expenditure with UK and local suppliers. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The way the spend data are collected flatters the local spend figures. Also, research by the North West Centre of Excellence, when I was director, suggested that local councils mostly used suppliers with whom business had been done for many years, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rather than</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> those likely to generate economic growth. Ways to increase local procurement include:</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Direct procurement spend towards those organisations that are most likely to grow and generate employment. This will often be the more innovative ones.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Direct procurement spend away from international supply chains towards companies that are prepared to invest in local companies and supply chains.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Develop a strategic joint approach to major suppliers and markets in order to influence them and encourage them to invest in the UK economy, for example, creating UK IT centres as opposed to ones overseas.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Work with suppliers to help them become more competitive.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Harmonise, simplify procurement procedures, processes, contract terms and conditions to make it easier for small, innovative suppliers to secure business.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Sophisticated approaches must be used to take cost and risk out of supply chains and products. Typical improvements may be 15%. Thus, councils will have more money to spend on front line services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> which should create more local employment. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Achieving the above requires expertise in all markets that few, if any, councils can afford if they act independently. Appropriate aggregation of procurement spend will help local government to use its economic power to achieve its objectives. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Collaboration accounts for just 15% of spend despite great commonality in products, services, suppliers and the knowledge and techniques needed. There is scope to increase this greatly.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Procurement exists to support councils </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">deliver the services that residents need. A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> local government owned </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">integrated procurement network, consisting of national and regional centres of expertise (please refer to the Appendix) would provide councils with the capability needed without impinging on local democracy. It is suggested that the LGA and SOLACE work up a proposal to create such a model</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, obtain support from sufficient councils </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and seek funding from DCLG to build-up the capability of the best procurement teams in local government into such centres and invest in improving commissioning. The precedent is that extra funding has been found to support radical procurement initiatives for the NHS and central government.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">17 November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">APPENDIX  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">INTEGRATED PROCUREMENT NETWORK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold"> CENTRES OF EXPERTISE</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Specialist National Centres:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.29pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Geographically distributed, with different centres having different specialisms</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.29pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Develop and implement strategies for investment and economic growth, taking into account national, regional and local needs</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.29pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Develop and implement strategies to secure maximum value for money for local government</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.29pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Manage major national categories</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.29pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Manage global and national suppliers</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.29pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Manage global and national markets and supply chains</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.29pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Manage and support the letting of the specialist (e.g. PFIs), largest and most complex contracts</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.29pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Provide specialist contracting expertise</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.29pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Determine the standard procedures, processes and contract terms and conditions to be used throughout local government.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Regional/Geographical Centres:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.29pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Develop and implement regional and more local strategies for investment and economic growth</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.29pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Develop and implement strategies to secure maximum value for money</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.29pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Manage procurement categories best done regionally</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.29pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Manage regional suppliers and supply chains</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.29pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Let and manage major and some specialist contracts </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.29pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Provide specialist contracting expertise</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Local Procurement</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.29pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Procure </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">and implement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">what is best </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">handled</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> locally</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Other Features</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.29pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">National and Regional centres to be part of a single integrated structure, with a chief executive</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.29pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Possible structure could be a ‘Mutual’ with o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">versight by a management board consisting of LGA, council leaders and chief executives, possibly with some non-executive directors</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.29pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Councils to choose at the outset whether to opt in. Those that didn’t, would have to stay out for an agreed period (e.g. 3 years)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.29pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The national and regional centres to be built on the best, e.g. the best councils and consortia</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.29pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Implementation at a measured pace over (say) 5 years</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.29pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Investment in centres of expertise to build up capability and high standards</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.29pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Some centres of expertise to have both national and regional roles</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.29pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Major consortia, e.g. YPO, could choose to remain independent, but would still operate as part of the overall framework</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.29pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Service level agreements to define the service that councils </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">sh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ould expect</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.29pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Performance measurement to ensure local government gets what it needs</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Commissioning</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Investment to improve standards of commissioning</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">17 November 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>